<section xid="3" props="page-margin-footer:0.5in; page-margin-header:0.5in">
<p style="Normal" xid="4" props="text-indent:0.5000in"><c></c><c>In this essay, I make a case for slowing down the movement acceleration in Overwatch. First, I will define the term and give examples of its use in various competitive FPS games. Next, I will analyze the current state of movement acceleration in Overwatch and its negative effects on the competitive nature of the game. Lastly, I will refute common objections to my case.</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="9" props="text-indent:0.0000in"><c props="font-weight:bold">Defining Movement Acceleration</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="2" props="text-indent:0.5000in"><c>Movement acceleration is the set of values that determine how quickly a character can reach a maximum top speed in a shooter game. Although players can have several ways to move around the map, movement acceleration generally applies to walking, i.e. only using WASD to move. In competitive FPS games, this value tends to be a static value; player movement ramps up linearly until the maximum walking speed is reached, upon which the player moves at that maximum speed until they choose to slow down or change direction.</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="6" props="text-indent:0.5000in"><c>This concept is an important component of the core shooting mechanics of a competitive FPS game. If acceleration is too high, player movement can become jittery and difficult to predict, as players would be able to change directions quicker than an opponent can track them with their crosshair. Too slow, and players being shot at will be too easy to hit and movement will feel sluggish.</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="7" props="text-indent:0.5000in"><c></c><c>Competitive shooters must strike a balance between these two extremes that fits the core shooting mechanics. A slower-paced game like Counter Strike: Global Offensive benefits from slower acceleration; it enforces tactical decision-making by combining slower acceleration with high inaccuracy while moving, and highly damaging guns. In CSGO, the minutiae are amplified in importance: how to properly round a corner that an enemy could be looking at, how to clear angles when pushing into a bombsite, proper grenade usage to block sight lines and advance to strong positions. On the other hand, higher acceleration in arena shooters like Quake Champions and Unreal Tournament promotes the use of skillful movement to dodge projectile weapons and take control of the items scattered around the map.</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="13" props="text-indent:0.0000in"><c props="font-weight:bold">Types </c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="10" props="text-indent:0.0000in"><c props="font-weight:bold">Game Sense vs. Mechanical Skill</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="11" props="text-indent:0.5000in"><c props="font-weight:normal">Every competitive FPS must strike a balance between promoting game sense and mechanical skill. Game sense is the combination of </c><c props="font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">knowledge</c><c props="font-weight:normal"> and </c><c props="font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">experience</c><c props="font-weight:normal"> that creates optimal play by minimizing mistakes, while mechanical skill is the raw aim and movement that come from </c><c props="font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">practice</c><c props="font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"></c><c props="font-weight:normal">. Any successful competitive FPS player must have both strong game sense and strong mechanical skill, but different games emphasize one over the other.</c></p>
</section>
